The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Tata Chem preferential float to promoter
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Tata Chem preferential float to promoter
          OUR BUREAU                                            
	May 24: Tata Chemicals plans to raise Rs 400 crore via a preferential issue to promoter company Tata Sons.         
	We plan to raise Rs 400 crore via preferential issue to Tata Sons in the current year, P.K. Ghosh, chief financial officer of Tata Chemicals, said here today.         
	The company will issue 1.15 crore shares.         
	The price of the proposed issue will be determined according to the applicable ICDR (issue of capital and disclosure requirements) regulations. At the current market price of Rs 300.30, the company will raise Rs 345.34 crore.         
	The company is also doubling its Babrala unit capacity to 24 lakh tonnes at an estimated cost of Rs 4,000 crore in the next three years. Babrala is in Uttar Pradesh.         
	The companys consolidated net profit stood at Rs 605.90 crore for the year ended March 31, 2010 against Rs 648 crore in the previous fiscal.        
	The figures of the corresponding period in the previous year are not comparable partly on account of Rallis India becoming a subsidiary of the company.         
	Total income stood at Rs 9,712.6 crore for 2009-10 compared with Rs 12,832.6 crore in the previous fiscal.         
	Sun Pharma net        
	Pharma major Sun Pharmaceuticals Industries has reported a marginal decline in its net profit for the quarter ended March 31 at Rs 394 crore against Rs 394.9 crore a year ago.        
	Net sales declined 2.2 per cent to Rs 1,109 crore from Rs 1,134 crore in the year-ago period.        
	Central Bank        
	The Central Bank of India today reported a 82.83 per cent growth in consolidated net profit for the year ended March 2010 at Rs 1,162.55 crore compared with Rs 635.85 crore in the year-ago period.        
	The board of directors has proposed a dividend of Rs 1.20 per share, or 12 per cent, for the financial year 2009-10.                                                                                                                                       
